{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643905"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:59:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:59:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18021"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18021"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10735"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73306"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10735"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18021"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58777"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24983"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24987"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24997"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73306"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAnatomically, the neck can be divided into a number of triangles. The anterior triangle is bordered by the sternocleidomastoid muscle, the inferior border of the mandible and the midline of the neck. There are a number of smaller triangles within the anterior triangle.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is considered to be a part of the anterior triangle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Occipital triangle","Posterior triangle","Submental triangle","Subclavian triangle","Supraclavicular triangle"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe neck is divided into two major triangles: the anterior and posterior triangles. The \u003Cstrong\u003Esubmental triangle\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the anterior triangle of the neck. It is located beneath the chin and is bounded by the anterior belly of the digastric muscles and the hyoid bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esupraclavicular triangle\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the posterior triangle of the neck, which is bounded by the posterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle, the anterior border of the trapezius muscle, and the clavicle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoccipital triangle\u003C/strong\u003E is also part of the posterior triangle, located above the supraclavicular triangle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior triangle\u003C/strong\u003E itself is not part of the anterior triangle; it is a separate major division of the neck.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubclavian triangle\u003C/strong\u003E is another name for the supraclavicular triangle, which is part of the posterior triangle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The anterior triangle of the neck is bounded by the midline of the neck, the anterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle, and the inferior border of the mandible.","The anterior triangle contains several smaller triangles, including the submental triangle, submandibular triangle, carotid triangle, and muscular triangle.","The supraclavicular triangle is part of the posterior triangle of the neck."],"references":["Fehrenbach, M. J., \u0026 Herring, S. W. (2015). Illustrated Anatomy of the Head and Neck-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534836/","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58777"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18021"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58777"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T11:18:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T11:19:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10735"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73306"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"t